text: When horror movies were first starting to evolve from the old black and white to Technicolor, things really jumped out of their graves. The Thing by John Carpenter, phenomenal. Tree was plot, setting, spooks, great detail, and so forth. Compared to Chucky and other slashers, but don't get me wrong I don't mind them here and there, The Chainsaw Massacre, the first and remake. Sadly around the 2000's horror hasn't much changed, the spooks are now a crutch. The  one movie that hits home with me is made by Guillermo Deltoro The Orphanage. Scary at times and yet has a twist for its ending. Horror survival, Your Next. Only in full blue moon something like this comes out. I am sure there is more to add but shortly to say, horror directors, get with it.

text: Okay so story time. My friend and I are horror movie fanatics. We don't jump much, but there's are moments. But we barely do. We found insidious be messing up clicking paranormal activity and watched insidious instead and fell in love. We saw the second one together. Well we were in theaters to see Ouija and this trailer came on. Now we didn't know it was Insidious 3, but when the hand came down we jumped. We heard the beginning of Tip Toe Through The Tulips and looked at each other, both of our minds blown, then we sat there flailing our arms around and trying not to cry out of excitement. People say the Insidious' are boring, but in my opinion they aren't, and this one looks as good, if not better as the rest. I'm counting down the days till it comes out and I'm excited.

text: Back when I was little, about 4-6, I was bored. And my parents were doing the laundry. And again I was bored so I just started knocking on our wooden wall, that wall showed the shadows of the trees outside. I just kept knocking, then a shadow of a small rag doll said hi. I looked outside but there was no doll at all. And the shadow was definitely the doll alone. There were no hands holding on to it. I knocked some more, it went away, then I knocked again it came back. I got scared so I ran to my parents and told them there was a shadow. When we went to the wall, the shadow of the doll was gone.

text: I just finished watching the movie, and I have to say that it was terrible. A huge disappointment. If you plan on watching the movie, I recommend not watching the trailer since it practically shows 80% of the jump scares. The first Insidious terrified me, and this was like a desperate attempt to keep the franchise going. The prequel was COMPLETELY unnecessary, and if you're looking for an interesting  story about the origin of the red man you will be sorely disappointed. There's so many jump scares to the point where it wasn't even scary anymore, and the demons don't have that sense of mystery and fright they once gave you. There's even parts where the psychic FIGHTS them and basically throws around these demons that are supposed to be terrifying and keep you at the edge of your seat. And don't even get me started on the dialogue. I've read fanfiction with better dialogue than this movie. Overall I'd give Insidious 3 a 2/5 stars.
